<font face="Comic Sans MS" size="2">
<table border="0" cellspacing="10">
<font size="5">substitute</font><br>
<br>
format:&nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp &nbsp&nbsp <a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-substitute">#substitute</a> [{text}] [{new text}]<br>
<br>
The [] signify optional arguments.<br>
<br>
Allows you to replace original text from the mud with different text, or<br>
delete it altogether.&nbsp&nbsp This is helpful for if you have a slow modem, or<br>
there is a lot of text sent during battles, and the like.&nbsp&nbsp the %0-9<br>
variables can be used to capture text and use it as part of the new output,<br>
and the ^ char is valid to only check the beginning of the line for the<br>
text specified.<br>
<br>
If a . is the only character in the new text argument, if the line is<br>
matched, it will be deleted.<br>
<br>
If only one argument is given, all subs that match the string are displayed.<br>
The * char is valid in this instance.&nbsp&nbsp See help wildcard.<br>
<br>
If no argument is given, all subs are displayed.<br>
<br>
examples:<br>
<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-sub">#sub</a> {leaves} {.}<br>
gag any line that has the word 'leaves' in it.<br>
<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-sub">#sub</a> {^Zoe%0} {ZOE%0}<br>
any line that starts with the name Zoe will be replaced by a line that<br>
starts with 'ZOE'<br>
<a href="http://ytin.sourceforge.net/cgi-bin/help.pl/ytin?c-sub">#sub</a> {%0massacres%1} {%0MASSACRES%1}<br>
replace all occurrences of 'massacres' with 'MASSACRES'<br>
<br>
